   "photo-caption" : "<p><a href=\"http://erikkwakkel.tumblr.com/post/83645212961/making-shakespeare-today-in-1616-william\" class=\"tumblr_blog\">erikkwakkel</a>:</p>\n\n<blockquote><p><strong>Making Shakespeare</strong></p>\n<p>Today in 1616 William Shakespeare died. His works have been enjoyed by generations of readers, which means that generations of printers have been busy editing and reprinting his texts. The images above are special. They are from the 1791 edition of The Bardâs âdramatic worksâ, as the title page has it, including his play Richard III. Except, these images donât show the actual book. You are looking at the proofs corrected by the editor George Steevens himself, which miraculously survived.</p>\n<p>The proofs show the editor at work. U<span>sing the 1790 text of Malone as a basis,</span><span>Â Steevens changed Shakespeareâs words into what he thought was the best text to print. Words were deleted (âguiltyâ and âmurderâ are crossed out), clarifications were added (a character exited âwith the bodyâ, penned next to it</span><span>), and entire passages appear to have been rewritten (note the pasted pieces of paper with Steevens handwritten text). The proofs seen here show how Shakespeare is prepared for a new generation of readers: his words were perfected to reach a new audience - and new buyers.</span></p>\n<p>Pic: Washington, Shakespeare Library,Â PR2752Â 1791-1802a v.1 Sh.Col. (<a href=\"http://www.worldcat.org/title/dramatic-works-of-shakspeare-revised-by-george-steevens/oclc/43135209\">This</a>Â Shakespeare edition of 1791).Â <a href=\"http://luna.folger.edu/luna/servlet/detail/FOLGERCM1~6~6~985648~168317:-Plays--1791--W--Bulmer-and-Co---Th?qvq=q:Call_Number%3D%22PR2752%2B1791-1802a%2Bv.1%2BSh.Col.%22;lc:FOLGERCM1~6~6&amp;mi=0&amp;trs=1\">Here</a>Â is my source and more information.</p></blockquote>",
